Here is an example of how to create a simple search bar using PHP:

**index.php**
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        #search-bar {
            width: 50%;
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h2>Search for something:</h2>

    <form action="" method="get">
        <input type="text" id="search-bar" name="query" placeholder="Enter your search query...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <?php
    // Check if the form has been submitted
    if (isset($_GET['query'])) {
        $query = $_GET['query'];
        // Connect to the database (replace with your own connection code)
        $conn = mysqli_connect("localhost", "username", "password", "database");

        // Prepare the query to search for the entered text
        $sql = "SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE column_name LIKE '%$query%'";

        // Execute the query and store the result in a variable
        $result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);

        // Display the results
        if (mysqli_num_rows($result) > 0) {
            echo "<h2>Results:</h2>";
            while ($row = mysqli_fetch_array($result)) {
                echo "<p>" . $row['column_name'] . "</p>";
            }
        } else {
            echo "<p>No results found.</p>";
        }

        // Close the database connection
        mysqli_close($conn);
    }
    ?>

</body>
</html>
```
**How it works:**

1. The form has an input field with a name of "query" and a submit button.
2. When the form is submitted, PHP checks if the "query" variable is set in the `$_GET` superglobal array.
3. If it is, PHP connects to the database (replace with your own connection code).
4. It prepares a query to search for the entered text in a specific column of a table.
5. The query is executed and the result is stored in a variable.
6. If there are any results, they are displayed on the page.

**Note:** This example uses MySQLi as the database extension, but you can replace it with your own connection code if using another database system.

Also, this is a very basic search implementation and does not include error handling or sanitization of user input. In a real-world application, you would want to add these features for security reasons.

**Tips:**

* Make sure to adjust the SQL query to match your specific database schema.
* Use prepared statements instead of concatenating variables into the query string to avoid SQL injection vulnerabilities.
* Add some error handling and logging to handle cases where the search query fails or returns no results.

